# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-accounting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] In layman's terms, anthropogenic metabolism indicates the human impact on the world by the modern industrialized world.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Much of these impacts include waste management, ecological footprints, water footprints, and flow analysis (i.e., the rate at which each human depleted the energy around them).
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most anthropogenic metabolism happens in developed countries.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] A water footprint is the amount of water that each person uses in their daily lives.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most of the world's water is salt water which cannot be used in human food or water supplies.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Therefore, the freshwater sources that were once plentiful are now being diminished due to anthropogenic metabolism of the growing population.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] The water footprint encompasses how much fresh water is needed for each consumer's needs.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Allan, "there is a huge impact of water use on stores of surface and groundwater and on flows to which water is returned after use.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] These impacts are shown to be particularly high for manufacturing industries.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] For example, that there are less than 10 economies worldwide that have a significant water surplus, but that these economies have successfully met, or have the potential to meet, the water deficits of the other 190 economies.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Consumers enjoy the delusion of food and water security provided by virtual water trade.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] In addition, the ecological footprint is a more economical and land-focused way of looking at human impact.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Developed countries tend to have higher ecological footprints, which do not strictly correspond to a country's total population.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] According to research by Dias de Oliveira, Vaughan and Rykiel, "The Ecological Footprint...is an accounting tool based on two fundamental concepts, sustainability and carrying capacity.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] One of the major cycles that humans can contribute to that cause a major impact on climate change is the nitrogen cycle.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] This comes from nitrogen fertilizers that humans use.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Gruber and Galloway have researched, "The massive acceleration of the nitrogen cycle caused by the production and industrial use of artificial nitrogen fertilizers worldwide has led to a range of environmental problems.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] The carbon cycle is another major contributor to climate change primarily from anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] A couple examples of how humans contribute to the carbon in the atmosphere is by burning fossil fuels and deforestation.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Impact of climate change extend beyond humans.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] There is a forecast for extinctions of species because of their habitats being affected.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] There are major impacts on the marine systems as a result of anthropogenic metabolism, according to Blaustein, the dramatic findings indicate that "every square kilometer [is] affected by some anthropogenic driver of ecological change".
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] The negative effects of anthropogenic metabolism are seen through the water footprint, ecological footprint, carbon cycle, and the nitrogen cycle.
[src:energy-accounting/anthropogenic-metabolism] Studies on the marine ecosystem that show major impacts by humans and developed countries which include more industries, thus more anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] There are two main motivations to improve energy efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Firstly, one motivation is to achieve cost savings during the operation of the appliance or process.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] However, installing an energy-efficient technology comes with an upfront cost, the capital cost.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The different types of costs can be analyzed and compared with a life-cycle assessment.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Another motivation for energy efficiency is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and hence work towards climate action.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] A focus on energy efficiency can also have a national security benefit because it can reduce the amount of energy that has to be imported from other countries.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency and renewable energy go hand in hand for sustainable energy policies.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] They are high priority actions in the energy hierarchy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy productivity, which measures the output and quality of goods and services per unit of energy input, can come from either reducing the amount of energy required to produce something, or from increasing the quantity or quality of goods and services from the same amount of energy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] From the point of view of an energy consumer, the main motivation of energy efficiency is often simply saving money by lowering the cost of purchasing energy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Additionally, from an energy policy point of view, there has been a long trend in a wider recognition of energy efficiency as the "first fuel", meaning the ability to replace or avoid the consumption of actual fuels.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Moreover, it has long been recognized that energy efficiency brings other benefits additional to the reduction of energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Some estimates of the value of these other benefits, often called *multiple benefits*, *co-benefits*, *ancillary benefits* or *non-energy benefits*, have put their summed value even higher than that of the direct energy benefits.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] These multiple benefits of energy efficiency include things such as reduced greenhouse gas emissions, reduced air pollution and improved health, and improved energy security.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Methods for calculating the monetary value of these multiple benefits have been developed, including e.g. the choice experiment method for improvements that have a subjective component (such as aesthetics or comfort) and Tuominen-Seppänen method for price risk reduction.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] When included in the analysis, the economic benefit of energy efficiency investments can be shown to be significantly higher than simply the value of the saved energy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency has proved to be a cost-effective strategy for building economies without necessarily increasing energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] For example, the state of California began implementing energy-efficiency measures in the mid-1970s, including building code and appliance standards with strict efficiency requirements.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] During the following years, California's energy consumption has remained approximately flat on a per capita basis while national US consumption doubled.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] As part of its strategy, California implemented a "loading order" for new energy resources that puts energy efficiency first, renewable electricity supplies second, and new fossil-fired power plants last.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] States such as Connecticut and New York have created quasi-public Green Banks to help residential and commercial building-owners finance energy efficiency upgrades that reduce emissions and cut consumers' energy costs.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy conservation is broader than energy efficiency in including active efforts to decrease energy consumption, for example through behaviour change, in addition to using energy more efficiently.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Examples of conservation without efficiency improvements are heating a room less in winter, using the car less, air-drying your clothes instead of using the dryer, or enabling energy saving modes on a computer.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] As with other definitions, the boundary between efficient energy use and energy conservation can be fuzzy, but both are important in environmental and economic terms.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency—using less energy to deliver the same goods or services, or delivering comparable services with less goods—is a cornerstone of many sustainable energy strategies.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The International Energy Agency (IEA) has estimated that increasing energy efficiency could achieve 40% of greenhouse gas emission reductions needed to fulfil the Paris Agreement's goals.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy can be conserved by increasing the technical efficiency of appliances, vehicles, industrial processes, and buildings.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] If the demand for energy services remains constant, improving energy efficiency will reduce energy consumption and carbon emissions.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] However, many efficiency improvements do not reduce energy consumption by the amount predicted by simple engineering models.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] This is because they make energy services cheaper, and so consumption of those services increases.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] For example, since fuel efficient vehicles make travel cheaper, consumers may choose to drive farther, thereby offsetting some of the potential energy savings.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Similarly, an extensive historical analysis of technological efficiency improvements has conclusively shown that energy efficiency improvements were almost always outpaced by economic growth, resulting in a net increase in resource use and associated pollution.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] These are examples of the direct rebound effect.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Estimates of the size of the rebound effect range from roughly 5% to 40%.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The rebound effect is likely to be less than 30% at the household level and may be closer to 10% for transport.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] A rebound effect of 30% implies that improvements in energy efficiency should achieve 70% of the reduction in energy consumption projected using engineering models.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Modern appliances, such as, freezers, ovens, stoves, dishwashers, clothes washers and dryers, use significantly less energy than older appliances.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Current energy-efficient refrigerators, for example, use 40 percent less energy than conventional models did in 2001.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Following this, if all households in Europe changed their more than ten-year-old appliances into new ones, 20 billion kWh of electricity would be saved annually, hence reducing CO2 emissions by almost 18 billion kg.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In the US, the corresponding figures would be 17 billion kWh of electricity and 27,000,000,000 lb (1.2×1010 kg) CO2.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] According to a 2009 study from McKinsey & Company the replacement of old appliances is one of the most efficient global measures to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Modern power management systems also reduce energy usage by idle appliances by turning them off or putting them into a low-energy mode after a certain time.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Many countries identify energy-efficient appliances using energy input labeling.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The impact of energy efficiency on peak demand depends on when the appliance is used.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] For example, an air conditioner uses more energy during the afternoon when it is hot.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Therefore, an energy-efficient air conditioner will have a larger impact on peak demand than off-peak demand.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] An energy-efficient dishwasher, on the other hand, uses more energy during the late evening when people do their dishes.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] This appliance may have little to no impact on peak demand.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Over the period 2001–2021, tech companies have replaced traditional silicon switches in an electric circuit with quicker gallium nitride transistors to make new gadgets as energy efficient as feasible.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Gallium nitride transistors are, however, more costly.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] This is a significant change in lowering the carbon footprint.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] A building's location and surroundings play a key role in regulating its temperature and illumination.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] For example, trees, landscaping, and hills can provide shade and block wind.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In cooler climates, designing northern hemisphere buildings with south facing windows and southern hemisphere buildings with north facing windows increases the amount of sun (ultimately heat energy) entering the building, minimizing energy use, by maximizing passive solar heating.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Tight building design, including energy-efficient windows, well-sealed doors, and additional thermal insulation of walls, basement slabs, and foundations can reduce heat loss by 25 to 50 percent.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Dark roofs may become up to 39 °C (70 °F) hotter than the most reflective white surfaces.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] They transmit some of this additional heat inside the building.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] US Studies have shown that lightly colored roofs use 40 percent less energy for cooling than buildings with darker roofs.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] White roof systems save more energy in sunnier climates.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Advanced electronic heating and cooling systems can moderate energy consumption and improve the comfort of people in the building.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Proper placement of windows and skylights as well as the use of architectural features that reflect light into a building can reduce the need for artificial lighting.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Increased use of natural and task lighting has been shown by one study to increase productivity in schools and offices.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Compact fluorescent lamps use two-thirds less energy and may last 6 to 10 times longer than incandescent light bulbs.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Newer fluorescent lights produce a natural light, and in most applications they are cost effective, despite their higher initial cost, with payback periods as low as a few months.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] LED lamps use only about 10% of the energy an incandescent lamp requires.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) is a rating system organized by the US Green Building Council (USGBC) to promote environmental responsibility in building design.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In 2013, USGBC developed the LEED Dynamic Plaque, a tool to track building performance against LEED metrics and a potential path to recertification.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The following year, the council collaborated with Honeywell to pull data on energy and water use, as well as indoor air quality from a BAS to automatically update the plaque, providing a near-real-time view of performance.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The USGBC office in Washington, D.C. is one of the first buildings to feature the live-updating LEED Dynamic Plaque.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Industries use a large amount of energy to power a diverse range of manufacturing and resource extraction processes.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Many industrial processes require large amounts of heat and mechanical power, most of which is delivered as natural gas, petroleum fuels, and electricity.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In addition some industries generate fuel from waste products that can be used to provide additional energy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Because industrial processes are so diverse it is impossible to describe the multitude of possible opportunities for energy efficiency in industry.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Many depend on the specific technologies and processes in use at each industrial facility.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] There are, however, a number of processes and energy services that are widely used in many industries.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Various industries generate steam and electricity for subsequent use within their facilities.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] When electricity is generated, the heat that is produced as a by-product can be captured and used for process steam, heating or other industrial purposes.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Conventional electricity generation is about 30% efficient, whereas combined heat and power (also called co-generation) converts up to 90 percent of the fuel into usable energy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Advanced boilers and furnaces can operate at higher temperatures while burning less fuel.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] These technologies are more efficient and produce fewer pollutants.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Over 45 percent of the fuel used by US manufacturers is burnt to make steam.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The typical industrial facility can reduce this energy usage 20 percent (according to the US Department of Energy) by insulating steam and condensate return lines, stopping steam leakage, and maintaining steam traps.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Electric motors usually run at a constant speed, but a variable speed drive allows the motor's energy output to match the required load.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] This achieves energy savings ranging from 3 to 60 percent, depending on how the motor is used.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Motor coils made of superconducting materials can also reduce energy losses.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Motors may also benefit from voltage optimization.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Industry uses a large number of pumps and compressors of all shapes and sizes and in a wide variety of applications.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The efficiency of pumps and compressors depends on many factors but often improvements can be made by implementing better process control and better maintenance practices.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Compressors are commonly used to provide compressed air which is used for sand blasting, painting, and other power tools.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] According to the US Department of Energy, optimizing compressed air systems by installing variable speed drives, along with preventive maintenance to detect and fix air leaks, can improve energy efficiency 20 to 50 percent.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The estimated energy efficiency for an automobile is 280 Passenger-Mile/106 Btu.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] There are several ways to enhance a vehicle's energy efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Using improved aerodynamics to minimize drag can increase vehicle fuel efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Reducing vehicle weight can also improve fuel economy, which is why composite materials are widely used in car bodies.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] More advanced tires, with decreased tire to road friction and rolling resistance, can save gasoline.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Fuel economy can be improved by up to 3.3% by keeping tires inflated to the correct pressure.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Replacing a clogged air filter can improve a cars fuel consumption by as much as 10 percent on older vehicles.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] On newer vehicles (1980s and up) with fuel-injected, computer-controlled engines, a clogged air filter has no effect on mpg but replacing it may improve acceleration by 6-11 percent.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Aerodynamics also aid in efficiency of a vehicle.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The design of a car impacts the amount of gas needed to move it through air.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Aerodynamics involves the air around the car, which can affect the efficiency of the energy expended.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Turbochargers can increase fuel efficiency by allowing a smaller displacement engine.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The 'Engine of the year 2011' is the Fiat TwinAir engine equipped with an MHI turbocharger.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] "Compared with a 1.2-liter 8v engine, the new 85 HP turbo has 23% more power and a 30% better performance index.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy-efficient vehicles may reach twice the fuel efficiency of the average automobile.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Cutting-edge designs, such as the diesel Mercedes-Benz Bionic concept vehicle have achieved a fuel efficiency as high as 84 miles per US gallon (2.8 L/100 km; 101 mpg‑imp), four times the current conventional automotive average.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The mainstream trend in automotive efficiency is the rise of electric vehicles (all-electric or hybrid electric).
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Electric engines have more than double the efficiency of internal combustion engines.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Hybrids, like the Toyota Prius, use regenerative braking to recapture energy that would dissipate in normal cars; the effect is especially pronounced in city driving.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Plug-in hybrids also have increased battery capacity, which makes it possible to drive for limited distances without burning any gasoline; in this case, energy efficiency is dictated by whatever process (such as coal-burning, hydroelectric, or renewable source) created the power.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Plug-ins can typically drive for around 40 miles (64 km) purely on electricity without recharging; if the battery runs low, a gas engine kicks in allowing for extended range.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Finally, all-electric cars are also growing in popularity.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Cities around the globe light up millions of streets with 300 million lights.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Some cities are seeking to reduce street light power consumption by dimming lights during off-peak hours or switching to LED lamps.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] LED lamps are known to reduce the energy consumption by 50% to 80%.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] There are several ways to improve aviation's use of energy through modifications aircraft and air traffic management.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Aircraft improve with better aerodynamics, engines and weight.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Seat density and cargo load factors contribute to efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Air traffic management systems can allow automation of takeoff, landing, and collision avoidance, as well as within airports, from simple things like HVAC and lighting to more complex tasks such as security and scanning.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] At the 2023 United Nations Climate Change Conference, one of the adopted declaration was the GLOBAL RENEWABLES AND ENERGY EFFICIENCY PLEDGE signed by 123 countries.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The declaration includes obligations to consider energy efficiency as "first fuel" and double the rate of increase in energy efficiency from 2% per year to 4% per year by the year 2030.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] China and India did not sign this pledge.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] International standards ISO 17743 and ISO 17742 provide a documented methodology for calculating and reporting on energy savings and energy efficiency for countries and cities.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The first EU-wide energy efficiency target was set in 1998.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Member states agreed to improve energy efficiency by 1 percent a year over twelve years.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In addition, legislation about products, industry, transport and buildings has contributed to a general energy efficiency framework.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] More effort is needed to address heating and cooling: there is more heat wasted during electricity production in Europe than is required to heat all buildings in the continent.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] All in all, EU energy efficiency legislation is estimated to deliver savings worth the equivalent of up to 326 million tons of oil per year by 2020.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The EU set itself a 20% energy savings target by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, but member states decide individually how energy savings will be achieved.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] At an EU summit in October 2014, EU countries agreed on a new energy efficiency target of 27% or greater by 2030.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] One mechanism used to achieve the target of 27% is the 'Suppliers Obligations & White Certificates'.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The ongoing debate around the 2016 Clean Energy Package also puts an emphasis on energy efficiency, but the goal will probably remain around 30% greater efficiency compared to 1990 levels.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Some have argued that this will not be enough for the EU to meet its Paris Agreement goals of reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 40% compared to 1990 levels.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In the European Union, 78% of enterprises proposed energy-saving methods in 2023, 67% listed energy contract renegotiation as a strategy, and 62% stated passing on costs to consumers as a plan to deal with energy market trends.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Larger organisations were found more likely to invest in energy efficiency, green innovation, and climate change, with a significant rise in energy efficiency investments reported by SMEs and mid-cap companies.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency is central to energy policy in Germany.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Progress toward improved efficiency has been steady.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Some however believe energy efficiency is still under-recognized in terms of its contribution to Germany's energy transformation (or *Energiewende*).
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Efforts to reduce final energy consumption in transport sector have not been successful, with a growth of 1.7% between 2005 and 2014.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] This growth is due to both road passenger and road freight transport.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Both sectors increased their overall distance travelled to record the highest figures ever for Germany.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Rebound effects played a significant role, both between improved vehicle efficiency and the distance travelled, and between improved vehicle efficiency and an increase in vehicle weights and engine power.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In 2014, the German federal government released its National Action Plan on Energy Efficiency (NAPE).
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The areas covered are the energy efficiency of buildings, energy conservation for companies, consumer energy efficiency, and transport energy efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In 2016, the German government released a green paper on energy efficiency for public consultation (in German).
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] It outlines the potential challenges and actions needed to reduce energy consumption in Germany over the coming decades.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] At the document's launch, economics and energy minister Sigmar Gabriel said "we do not need to produce, store, transmit and pay for the energy that we save".
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The green paper prioritizes the efficient use of energy as the "first" response and also outlines opportunities for sector coupling, including using renewable power for heating and transport.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Other proposals include a flexible energy tax which rises as petrol prices fall, thereby incentivizing fuel conservation despite low oil prices.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In Spain, four out of every five buildings use more energy than they should.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] They are either inadequately insulated or consume energy inefficiently.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The Unión de Créditos Immobiliarios (UCI), which has operations in Spain and Portugal, is increasing loans to homeowners and building management groups for energy-efficiency initiatives.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] Their Residential Energy Rehabilitation initiative aims to remodel and encourage the use of renewable energy in at least 3720 homes in Madrid, Barcelona, Valencia, and Seville.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The works are expected to mobilize around €46.5 million in energy efficiency upgrades by 2025 and save approximately 8.1 GWh of energy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] It has the ability to reduce carbon emissions by 7,545 tonnes per year.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In May 2016 Poland adopted a new Act on Energy Efficiency, to enter into force on 1 October 2016.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In July 2009, the Council of Australian Governments, which represents the individual states and territories of Australia, agreed to a National Strategy on Energy Efficiency (NSEE).
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] This is a ten-year plan accelerating the implementation of a nationwide adoption of energy-efficient practices and a preparation for the country's transformation into a low carbon future.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The overriding agreement that governs this strategy is the National Partnership Agreement on Energy Efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] In August 2017, the Government of Canada released Build Smart - Canada's Buildings Strategy, as a key driver of the Pan-Canadian Framework on Clean Growth and Climate Change, Canada's national climate strategy.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] A 2011 Energy Modeling Forum study covering the United States examined how energy efficiency opportunities will shape future fuel and electricity demand over the next several decades.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] The US economy is already set to lower its energy and carbon intensity, but explicit policies will be necessary to meet climate goals.
[src:energy-accounting/efficient-energy-use] These policies include: a carbon tax, mandated standards for more efficient appliances, buildings and vehicles, and subsidies or reductions in the upfront costs of new more energy-efficient equipment.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] Energy accounting is a system used in energy management systems to measure and analyze energy consumption to improve energy efficiency within an organization.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] Organisations such as Intel corporation use these systems to track energy usage.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] Various energy transformations are possible.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] An energy balance can be used to track energy through a system.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] This becomes a useful tool for determining resource use and environmental impacts.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] How much energy is needed at each point in a system is measured, as well as the form of that energy.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] An accounting system keeps track of energy in, energy out, and non-useful energy versus work done, and transformations within a system.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] Sometimes, non-useful work is what is often responsible for environmental problems.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-accounting] Energy returned on energy invested (EROEI) is the ratio of energy delivered by an energy technology to the energy invested to set up the technology.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] The journal is abstracted and indexed in the Social Sciences Citation Index, Scopus, EBSCO databases, Current Contents/Social & Behavioral Sciences, and Compendex.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal had a 2021 impact factor of 2.945, ranking it 65th out of 125 journals in the category "Environmental Studies".
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] The journal was first published in 1989; David Everest (Department of the Environment, United Kingdom) was its founding editor.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] Following his death in 1998, Boehmer-Christiansen became the journal's editor.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] She and several members of the journal's editorial advisory board had previously been associated with "the Energy and Environment Groups" at the Science and Technology Policy Unit (University of Sussex), with John Surrey.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] Its publisher, Multi-science ceased trading on 31 December 2015 and the journal was transferred to SAGE.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] In May 2017, Yiu Fai Tsang became the journal's editor.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] The journal was regarded as "a small journal that caters to climate change denialists".
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] It has played an important role in attacking climate science and scientists, for example Michael E.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] In 2011, a number of scientists such Gavin Schmidt, Roger A.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] Pielke Jr., Stephan Lewandowsky and Michael Ashley have criticised that *E&E* has low standards of peer review and little impact.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] When asked about the publication in the Spring of 2003 of a revised version of the paper at the center of the Soon and Baliunas controversy, Boehmer-Christiansen said, "I'm following my political agenda -- a bit, anyway.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-and-environment] The journal has also been accused of publishing papers that could not have passed any reasonable peer review process, such as one in 2011 that claimed that the Sun was made of iron.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] From a societal and economic perspective, "energy consumption" often refers to the use of energy resources by human civilization to power homes, industries, transportation, and other activities.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] This typically involves drawing upon various primary energy sources, including fossil fuels (coal, oil, natural gas), nuclear power, and renewable sources (solar, wind, hydro, geothermal).
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] The scale and patterns of this consumption have significant implications for environmental sustainability, economic development, and geopolitical stability.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] Analyzing trends in global and regional energy consumption helps policymakers and researchers understand resource availability, greenhouse gas emissions, and the potential for transitioning to more sustainable energy systems.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] In electrical engineering, "energy consumption" specifically refers to the amount of electrical energy utilized by a device, circuit, or system over a period of time.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] This is distinct from "power," which is the rate at which energy is consumed or transferred.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] While power is measured in watts (W) or kilowatts (kW), energy consumption is typically measured in watt-hours (Wh) or kilowatt-hours (kWh).
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] Electrical engineers are deeply concerned with energy consumption for several critical reasons.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] First, it directly impacts operational costs for consumers and industries, as electricity bills are calculated based on kWh consumed.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] Second, energy consumption is inextricably linked to energy efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] An efficient electrical system or device converts a larger proportion of input electrical energy into its desired output (e.g., light, motion, computation) and minimizes conversion into undesirable forms, primarily heat.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] Understanding and optimizing energy consumption is therefore crucial for designing systems that are not only effective but also sustainable and cost-effective, leading to advancements in areas like power electronics, smart grids, and low-power integrated circuits.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] In the body, energy consumption is part of energy homeostasis.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-consumption] Energy consumption in the body is a product of the basal metabolic rate and the physical activity level.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Energy management software often provides tools for reducing energy costs and consumption for buildings, communities or industries.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] By analyzing data from solar monitoring systems, companies gain a precise picture of both energy production and system performance.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] This makes it possible to measure savings potential and offers a clear snapshot of the installation's financial health.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] EMS collects energy data and uses it for three main purposes: Reporting, Monitoring and Engagement.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Reporting may include verification of energy data, benchmarking, and setting high-level energy use reduction targets.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Monitoring may include trend analysis and tracking energy consumption to identify cost-saving opportunities.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Engagement can mean real-time responses (automated or manual), or the initiation of a dialogue between occupants and building managers to promote energy conservation.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] One engagement method that has recently gained popularity is the real-time energy consumption display available in web applications or an onsite energy dashboard/display.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Energy Management Software collects historic and/or real-time interval data, with intervals varying from quarterly billing statements to minute-by-minute smart meter readings.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] In addition to energy consumption, an EMS collects data related to variables that impact energy consumption such as number of people in the building, outside temperature, number of produced units, and more.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] The data are collected from interval meters, a building automation system, directly from utilities, directly from sensors on electrical circuits, or other sources.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Past bills can be used to provide a comparison between pre- and post-EMS energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Through Energy Data Analytics, EMS assists the users in the composition of mathematical formulas for analyzing, forecasting and tracking energy conservation measures to quantify the success of the measure, once implemented.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Reporting tools are targeted at owners and executives who want to automate energy and emissions auditing.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Cost and consumption data from a number of buildings can be aggregated or compared with the software, saving time relative to manual reporting.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] EMS offers more detailed energy information than utility billing can provide; another advantage is that outside factors affecting energy use, such as weather condition or building occupancy, can be accounted for as part of the reporting process.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] This information can be used to prioritize energy savings initiatives and balance energy savings against energy-related capital expenditures.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Bill verification can be used to compare metered consumption against billed consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Bill analysis can also demonstrate the impact of different energy costs, for example by comparing electrical demand charges to consumption costs.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Greenhouse gas (GHG) accounting can calculate direct or indirect GHG emissions, which may be used for internal reporting or enterprise carbon accounting.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Monitoring tools track and display real-time and historical data.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Often, EMS includes various benchmarking tools, such as energy consumption per square foot, weather normalization or more advanced analysis using energy modelling algorithms to identify anomalous consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Seeing exactly when energy is used, combined with anomaly recognition, can allow Facility or Energy Managers to identify savings opportunities.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Initiatives such as demand shaving, replacement of malfunctioning equipment, retrofits of inefficient equipment, and removal of unnecessary loads can be discovered and coordinated using the EMS.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] For example, an unexpected energy spike at a specific time each day may indicate an improperly set or malfunctioning timer.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] These tools can also be used for Energy Monitoring and Targeting.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] EMS uses models to correct for variable factors such as weather when performing historical comparisons to verify the effect of conservation and efficiency initiatives.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] EMS may offer alerts, via text or email messages, when consumption values exceed pre-defined thresholds based on consumption or cost.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] These thresholds may be set at absolute levels, or use an energy model to determine when consumption is abnormally high or low.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] More recently, smartphones and tablets are becoming mainstream platforms for EMS.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Engagement can refer to automated or manual responses to collected and analyzed energy data.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Building control systems can respond as readily to energy fluctuation as a heating system can respond to temperature variation.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Demand spikes can trigger equipment power-down processes, with or without human intervention..
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Furthermore, modern energy management platforms are evolving to include integrated action management systems that bridge the gap between identifying a data anomaly and executing a physical fix.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] By formalizing accountability through structured workflows, these ecosystems improve engagement at the "action ownership" level, ensuring that data-driven insights lead to verified energy savings.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Another objective of Engagement is to connect occupants’ daily choices with building energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] By displaying real-time consumption information, occupants see the immediate impact of their actions.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] The software can be used to promote energy conservation initiatives, offer advice to the occupants, or provide a forum for feedback on sustainability initiatives.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] People-driven energy conservation programs, such as those sponsored by Energy Education, can be highly effective in reducing energy use and cost.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management-software] Letting occupants know their real-time consumption alone can be responsible for a 7% reduction in energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Energy management objectives are resource conservation, climate protection and cost savings, while the users have permanent access to the energy they need.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It is connected closely to environmental management, production management, logistics and other established business functions.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It is a systematic endeavor to optimize energy efficiency for specific political, economic, and environmental objectives through engineering and management techniques.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] One of the initial steps for an effective energy cost control program is the base line energy assessment, which examines the pattern of existing energy usage by the government or any sub-entity of the government or private organization.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] This program will set the reference point for improvements in energy efficiency.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Energy efficiency can improve the existing energy usage and benchmarking of every individual section such as area, sub-area, and the industry.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It is important to integrate the energy management in the organizational structure, so that the energy management can be implemented.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Responsibilities and the interaction of the decision makers should be regularized.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The delegation of functions and competencies extend from the top management to the executive worker.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Furthermore, a comprehensive coordination can ensure the fulfillment of the tasks.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It is advisable to establish a separate organizational unit "energy management" in large or energy-intensive companies.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] This unit supports the senior management and keeps track.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It depends on the basic form of the organizational structure, where this unit is connected.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In case of a functional organization the unit is located directly between the first (CEO) and the second hierarchical level (corporate functions such as production, procurement, marketing).
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In a divisional organization, there should be a central and several sector-specific energy management units.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] So the diverse needs of the individual sectors and the coordination between the branches and the head office can be fulfilled.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In a matrix organization the energy management can be included as a matrix function and thus approach most functions directly.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Facility management is an important part of energy management, because a huge proportion (average 25 per cent) of complete operating costs are energy costs.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The central task of energy management is to reduce costs for the provision of energy in buildings and facilities without compromising work processes.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Especially the availability and service life of the equipment and the ease of use should remain the same.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The German Facility Management Association (GEFMA e.V.) has published guidelines (e.g.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] GEFMA 124-1 and 124–2), which contain methods and ways of dealing with the integration of energy management in the context of a successful facility management.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In this topic the facility manager has to deal with economic, ecological, risk-based and quality-based targets.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] He tries to minimize the total cost of the energy-related processes (supply, distribution and use).
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The most important key figure in this context is kilowatt-hours per square meter per year (kWh/m2a).
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Based on this key figure properties can be classified according to their energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In comparison, the passive house ultra-low-energy standard, currently undergoing adoption in some other European countries, has a maximum space heating requirement of 15 kWh/m2a.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] A passive house is a very well insulated and virtually airtight building.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It does not require a conventional heating system.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It is heated by solar gain and internal gains from people.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] There are also buildings that produce more energy (for example by solar water heating or photovoltaic systems) over the course of a year than it imports from external sources.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] These buildings are called energy-plus-houses.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In addition, the work regulations manage competencies, roles and responsibilities.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Because the systems also include risk factors (e.g. oil tanks, gas lines), you must ensure that all tasks are clearly described and distributed.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] A clear regulation can help to avoid liability risks.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In facility management, energy management systems are used to monitor and control building systems such as heating, ventilation, and lighting.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Integration with automation technologies enables more efficient operation of facilities and reduced energy consumption.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Logistics is the management of the flow of resources between the point of origin and the point of destination in order to meet some requirements - for example of customers or corporations.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Especially the core logistics task, transportation of the goods, can save costs and protect the environment through efficient energy management.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The relevant factors are the choice of means of transportation, duration and length of transportation, and cooperation with logistics service providers.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Transport logistics accounts for more than 24% of CO2 emissions worldwide.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] For this reason Green Logistics has become more prevalent in business.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Besides transportation of goods, the transport of persons should be an important part of the logistic strategy of organizations.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] For business trips, it can be important to attract attention to the choice and the proportionality of the means of transport.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It can be balanced whether a physical presence is mandatory or a telephone or video conference is just as useful.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Home Office is another possibility in which the company can protect the environment indirectly.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Procurement is the acquisition of goods or services.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Energy prices fluctuate constantly, which can significantly affect the energy bill of organizations.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Therefore, poor energy procurement decisions can be expensive.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Organizations can control and reduce energy costs by taking a proactive and efficient approach to buying energy.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Even a change of the energy source can be a profitable and eco-friendly alternative.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Production is the act of creating output, a good or service which has value and contributes to the utility of individuals.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] This central process may differ depending on the industry.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Industrial companies have facilities that require a lot of energy.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Service companies, in turn, do not need many materials, their energy-related focus is mainly facility management or Green IT.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Therefore, the energy-related focus has to be identified first, then evaluated and optimized.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Production is typically the area with the largest energy consumption within an organization.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Therefore, also the production planning and control becomes very important.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It deals with the operational, temporal, quantitative and spatial planning, control and management of all processes that are necessary in the production of goods and commodities.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The "production planner" should plan the production processes so that they operate in an energy efficient way.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] For example, a strong power consumer can be moved into the night time.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Peaks should be avoided for the benefit of a unified load profile.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The impending changes in the structure of energy production require an increasing demand for storage capacity.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The production planning and control has to deal with the problem of limited storability of energy.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In principle there is the possibility to store energy electrically, mechanically, or chemically.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Another trend-setting technology is lithium-based electrochemical storage, which can be used in electric vehicles or as an option to control the power grid.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The German Federal Ministry of Economics and Technology realized the significance of this topic and established an initiative with the aim to promote technological breakthroughs and support the rapid introduction of new energy storage.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Maintenance is the combination of all technical and administrative actions, including supervision actions, intended to retain an item in, or restore it to, a state in which it can perform a required function.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Detailed maintenance is essential to support the energy management.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Hereby power losses and cost increases can be avoided.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Energy efficiency and management is key for industries worldwide.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] A long-term energy strategy should be part of the overall strategy of a company.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] This strategy may include the objective of increasing the use of renewable energies.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Furthermore, criteria for decisions on energy investments, such as yield expectations, are determined.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] By formulating an energy strategy companies have the opportunity to avoid risks and to assure a competitive advance against their business rivals.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In reality, you usually find hybrid forms of different strategies.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Many companies are trying to promote its image and time protect the climate through a proactive and public energy strategy.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] General Motors (GM) strategy is based on continuous improvement.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Furthermore, they have six principles: e.g. restoring and preserving the environment, reducing waste and pollutants, educating the public about environmental conservation, collaboration for the development of environmental laws and regulations.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Nokia created its first climate strategy in 2006.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The strategy tries to evaluate the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of products and operations and sets reduction targets accordingly.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Furthermore, their environmental efforts is based on four key issues: substance management, energy efficiency, recycling, promoting environmental sustainability.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The energy strategy of Volkswagen (VW) is based on environmentally friendly products and a resource-efficient production according to the "Group Strategy 2018".
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Almost all locations of the Group are certified to the international standard ISO 14001 for environmental management systems.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Greenwashing is the incorporation of green strategies to create an environmentally friendly image of an organization, despite action indicating otherwise.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] It can be weaponized to delay environmental action.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Even many countries formulate energy strategies.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The Swiss Federal Council decided in May 2011 to resign nuclear energy medium-dated.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The nuclear power plants will be shut down at the end of life and will not be replaced.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] In Compensation they put the focus on energy efficiency, renewable energies, fossil energy sources and the development of water power.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The European Union has clear instructions for its members.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The "20-20-20-targets" include, that the Member States have to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% below 1990 levels, increase energy efficiency by 20% and achieve a 20% share of renewable energy in total energy consumption by 2020.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] The basis of every energy strategy is the corporate culture and the related ethical standards applying in the company.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Ethics, in the sense of business ethics, examines ethical principles and moral or ethical issues that arise in a business environment.
[src:energy-accounting/energy-management] Ethical standards can appear in company guidelines, energy and environmental policies or other documents.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] When the EROI of a source of energy is less than or equal to one, that energy source becomes a net "energy sink" and can no longer be used as a source of energy.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] A related measure, called **energy stored on energy invested** (**ESOEI**), is used to analyse storage systems.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] To be considered viable as a prominent fuel or energy source, a fuel or energy must have an EROI ratio of at least 3:1.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The energy analysis field of study is credited with being popularised by Charles A.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Hall, a systems ecology and biophysical economics professor at the State University of New York.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Hall applied the biological methodology developed at an Ecosystems Marine Biological Laboratory, and then adapted that method to research human industrial civilisation.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The concept would have its greatest exposure in 1984, with a paper by Hall that appeared on the cover of the journal *Science*.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Gauging the EROI of photovoltaic technologies proves to be difficult and is still the subject of numerous studies.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] This is mainly due to "energy invested" varying depending on technology, methodology, and system boundary assumptions, resulting in a range from a maximum of 2000 kWh/m2 of module area down to a minimum of 300 kWh/m2, with a median value of 585 kWh/m2 according to a meta-study from 2013.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Regarding output, it depends on the local insolation, not just the system itself, so assumptions have to be made.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Some studies (see below) include in their analysis that photovoltaic cells produce electricity, while the invested energy may be lower grade primary energy.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] A 2015 review in Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews assessed the energy payback time and EROI of a variety of PV module technologies.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In this study, which uses an insolation of 1700 kWh/m2/yr and a system lifetime of 30 years, mean harmonised EROIs between 8.7 and 34.2 were found.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Mean harmonised energy payback time varied from 1.0 to 4.1 years.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In 2021, the Fraunhofer Institute for Solar Energy Systems calculated an energy payback time of around 1 year for European PV installations (0.9 years for Catania in Southern Italy, 1.1 years for Brussels) with wafer-based silicon PERC cells.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In the scientific literature EROIs wind turbines is around 16 unbuffered and 4 buffered.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Data collected in 2018 found that the EROI of operational wind turbines averaged 19.8 with high variability depending on wind conditions and wind turbine size.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] EROIs tend to be higher for recent wind turbines compared to older technology wind turbines.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Vestas reports an EROI of 31 for its V150 model wind turbine.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The EROI for hydropower plants averages about 110 when it is run for about 100 years.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] One study found that in 1970, oil sand net energy returns were about 1.0, but by 2010 had increased to about 5.23.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Conventional sources of oil have a rather large variation depending on various geologic factors.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The EROI for refined fuel from conventional oil sources varies from around 18 to 43.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Due to the process heat input requirements for oil shale harvesting, the EROI is low.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Typically, natural gas is used, either directly combusted for process heat or used to power an electricity-generating turbine, which then uses electrical heating elements to heat the underground layers of shale to produce oil from the kerogen.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The resulting EROI is typically around 1.4–1.5.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The weighted average standard EROI of all oil liquids (including coal-to-liquids, gas-to-liquids, biofuels, etc.) is expected to decrease from 44.4 in 1950 to 6.7 in 2050.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The standard EROI for natural gas is estimated to decrease from 141.5 in 1950 to an apparent plateau of 16.8 in 2050.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The EROI for nuclear plants ranges from 20 to 81.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The natural or primary energy sources are not included in the calculation of energy invested, only the human-applied sources.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] For example, in the case of biofuels, the solar insolation driving photosynthesis is not included, and the energy used in the stellar synthesis of fissile elements is not included for nuclear fission.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The energy returned includes only human usable energy and not wastes such as waste heat.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Nevertheless, heat of any form can be counted where it is actually used for heating.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] However, the use of waste heat in district heating and water desalination in cogeneration plants is rare, and in practice it is often excluded in EROI analysis of energy sources.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In more recent years, however, a source of continued controversy is the creation of a different methodology endorsed by certain members of the IEA which for example most notably in the case of photovoltaic solar panels, controversially generates more favorable values.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In the case of photovoltaic solar panels, the IEA method tends to focus on the energy used in the factory process alone.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In 2016, Hall observed that much of the published work in this field is produced by advocates or persons with a connection to business interests among the competing technologies, and that government agencies had not yet provided adequate funding for rigorous analysis by more neutral observers.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] EROI and *Net energy (gain)* measure the same quality of an energy source or sink in numerically different ways.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Net energy describes the amounts, while EROI measures the ratio or efficiency of the process.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] For example, given a process with an EROI of 5, expending 1 unit of energy yields a net energy gain of 4 units.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The break-even point happens with an EROI of 1 or a net energy gain of 0.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The time to reach this break-even point is called energy payback period (EPP) or energy payback time (EPBT).
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Although many qualities of an energy source matter (for example, oil is energy-dense and transportable, while wind is variable), when the EROI of the main sources of energy for an economy fall, that energy becomes more difficult to obtain and its relative price may increase.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] With regard to fossil fuels, when oil was originally discovered, it took on average one barrel of oil to find, extract, and process about 100 barrels of oil.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The ratio, for discovery of fossil fuels in the United States, has declined steadily over the last century from about 1000:1 in 1919 to only 5:1 in the 2010s.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Since the invention of agriculture, humans have increasingly used exogenous sources of energy to multiply human muscle power.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Some historians have attributed this largely to more easily exploited (i.e. higher EROI) energy sources, which is related to the concept of energy slaves.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Thomas Homer-Dixon argues that a falling EROI in the Later Roman Empire was one of the reasons for the collapse of the Western Empire in the fifth century CE.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In "The Upside of Down", he suggests that EROI analysis provides a basis for the analysis of the rise and fall of civilisations.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Looking at the maximum extent of the Roman Empire, (60 million) and its technological base, the agrarian base of Rome was about 1:12 per hectare for wheat and 1:27 for alfalfa (giving a 1:2.7 production for oxen).
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] One can then use this to calculate the population of the Roman Empire required at its height, based on about 2,500–3,000 calories per day per person.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] It comes out roughly equal to the area of food production at its height.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] But ecological damage (deforestation, soil fertility loss, particularly in southern Spain, southern Italy, Sicily and especially north Africa) saw a collapse in the system beginning in the 2nd century, as EROI began to fall.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] It bottomed in 1084 when Rome's population, which had peaked under Trajan at 1.5 million, was only 15,000.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Evidence also fits the cycle of Mayan and Cambodian collapse too.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Joseph Tainter suggests that diminishing returns of the EROI is a chief cause of the collapse of complex societies, which has been suggested as caused by peak wood in early societies.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Newer research (2024) found that if EROIs are measured at the stage of useful energy rather than final energy, EROI of fossil fuels are lower than electricity producing renewable energies, even if intermittency is accounted for.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] EROI is calculated by dividing the energy output by the energy input.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Measuring total energy output is often easy, especially in the case of an electrical output, where some appropriate electricity meter can be used.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] However, researchers disagree on how to determine energy input accurately and therefore arrive at different numbers for the same source of energy.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] How deep should the probing in the supply chain of the tools being used to generate energy go?
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] For example, if steel is being used to drill for oil or construct a nuclear power plant, should the energy input of the steel be taken into account?
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Should the energy input into building the factory being used to construct the steel be taken into account and amortised?
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Should the energy input of the roads which are used to ferry the goods be taken into account?
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] What about the energy used to cook the steelworkers' breakfasts?
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] These are complex questions evading simple answers.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] A full accounting would require considerations of opportunity costs and comparing total energy expenditures in the presence and absence of this economic activity.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] However, when comparing two energy sources, a standard practice for the supply chain energy input can be adopted.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] For example, consider the steel, but don't consider the energy invested in factories deeper than the first level in the supply chain.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Richards and Watt propose an *Energy Yield Ratio* for photovoltaic systems as an alternative to EROI (which they refer to as *Energy Return Factor*).
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The difference is that it uses the design lifetime of the system, which is known in advance, rather than the actual lifetime.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] This also means that it can be adapted to multi-component systems where the components have different lifetimes.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Another issue with EROI that many studies attempt to tackle is that the energy returned can be in different forms, and these forms can have different utility.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] For example, electricity can be converted more efficiently than thermal energy into motion, due to electricity's lower entropy.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In addition, the form of energy of the input can be completely different from the output.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] For example, energy in the form of coal could be used in the production of ethanol.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] This might have an EROI of less than one, but could still be desirable due to the benefits of liquid fuels (assuming the latter are not used in the processes of extraction and transformation).
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] There are three prominent expanded EROI calculations: point of use, extended, and societal.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Point of Use EROI expands the calculation to include the cost of refining and transporting the fuel during the refining process.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Since this expands the bounds of the calculation to include more production processes, EROI will decrease.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Extended EROI provides point of use expansions, as well as the cost of creating the infrastructure needed for transportation of the energy or fuel once refined.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Societal EROI is the sum of all the EROIs of all the fuels used in a society or nation.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] A societal EROI has never been calculated, and researchers believe it may currently be impossible to know all variables necessary to complete the calculation, but attempted estimates have been made for some nations.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Calculations are done by summing all of the EROIs for domestically produced and imported fuels and comparing the result to the Human Development Index (HDI), a tool often used to understand well-being in a society.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] According to this calculation, the amount of energy a society has available to it increases the quality of life for the people living in that country, and countries with less energy available also have a harder time satisfying citizens' basic needs.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] This is to say that societal EROI and overall quality of life are very closely linked.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The following table is a compilation of sources of energy, taken from a review paper published in 2022.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] ESOEI (or ESOIe) is used when EROI is below 1.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] A related recent concern is energy cannibalism, where energy technologies can have a limited growth rate if climate neutrality is demanded.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Many energy technologies are capable of replacing significant volumes of fossil fuels and concomitant greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Unfortunately, neither the enormous scale of the current fossil fuel energy system nor the necessary growth rate of these technologies is well understood within the limits imposed by the net energy produced for a growing industry.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] This technical limitation is known as energy cannibalism and refers to an effect where rapid growth of an entire energy-producing or energy efficiency industry creates a need for energy that uses (or cannibalises) the energy of existing power plants or production plants.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The solar breeder overcomes some of these problems.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] A solar breeder is a photovoltaic panel manufacturing plant which can be made energy-independent by using energy derived from its own roof using its own panels.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Such a plant becomes not only energy self-sufficient but a major supplier of new energy, hence the name solar breeder.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] Research on the concept was conducted by Centre for Photovoltaic Engineering, University of New South Wales, Australia.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The reported investigation establishes certain mathematical relationships for the solar breeder which indicate that a vast amount of net energy is available from such a plant for the indefinite future.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] The solar module processing plant at Frederick, Maryland was originally planned as such a solar breeder.
[src:energy-accounting/eroei] In 2009 the Sahara Solar Breeder Project was proposed by the *Science Council of Japan* as a cooperation between Japan and Algeria with the highly ambitious goal of creating hundreds of GW of capacity within 30 years.
